The operator `T` is said to have restricted weak type `(p, q, c)` if for every `f : α → E` which is `p`-locally integrable and `‖f‖_L^p ≤ 1`, we have `‖T(f)‖_L^q ≤ c`.
This is equivalent to `‖T(f)‖_L^q ≤ c ‖f‖_L^p` for all `f` which are `p`-locally integrable.

The main theorem states that if `T` has restricted weak type `(p, p', c)` for some `c > 0`, then `T` is weakly continuous, i.e., `‖T(f)‖_L^p ≤ ‖f‖_L^p` for all `f` which are `p`-locally integrable.

